    "summary": "Knossos, on the north coast of Crete near modern Heraklion, was settled in the Neolithic period and developed into a significant early Bronze Age community approximately 2700–2000 BC — the period known as Early Minoan. During these centuries, before the great palace complexes that would define the Minoan civilisation's peak, Knossos was already one of the largest settlements on Crete, with evidence of craft specialisation, local trade networks, and the beginning of the monumental building traditions that would flower in the following millennium.\n\nThe Early Minoan period on Crete saw the development of distinctive burial practices, including the use of circular 'tholos' tombs in southern Crete and rectangular ossuaries in the north. Material culture of this period reflects growing sophistication in pottery, metalworking, and seal-cutting, as well as trade contacts with the Cycladic islands, mainland Greece, and the Levant. Gold jewellery of remarkable quality has been recovered from Early Minoan tombs, suggesting an already-developed elite culture with access to imported precious materials.\n\nThe site of Knossos would go on to become the centre of Minoan palatial civilisation from approximately 2000 BC onward, with the construction of the First Palace and eventually the famous architectural complex excavated by Arthur Evans at the turn of the twentieth century. The early settlement at Knossos thus represents the deep roots of a civilisation that would become one of the most influential in the prehistoric Aegean world, laying cultural and social foundations upon which the palace society of the second millennium BC would be built.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knossos",
